7 NEW SECTION. Section 2. Minimum nurse-to-patient ratios. (1) A hospital licensed by the
8 department of public health and human services may not assign a nurse:
9 (a) in an emergency room, to more than four nontrauma or noncritical care patients or to more than
10 one trauma or critical care patient, except in circumstances that require two or more nurses to be assigned to
11 one patient;
12 (b) in an intensive care unit, to more than two patients, except when circumstances require one or
13 more nurses to be assigned to one patient;
14 (c) in a labor and delivery unit, to more than one patient experiencing complications or who is
15 actively in labor or to more than two patients who are not experiencing complications or who are actively in
16 labor;
17 (d) in a postpartum unit or nursery, to more than six patients, counting mother and baby each as
18 separate patients;
19 (e) in an operating room, to more than one patient;
20 (f) in an oncology unit, to more than five patients;
21 (g) in a postanesthesia care unit, to more than two patients;
22 (h) in an intermediate care unit, to more than four patients;
23 (i) in a medical-surgical unit, to more than five patients;
24 (j) in a cardiac telemetry unit, to more than four patients;
25 (k) in a psychiatric unit, to more than six patients; and
26 (l) in a pediatric unit, to more than four patients.
27 (2) As used in this section, "nurse" has the same MEANING as PROVIDED in [section 1].
